Singleton ensures a class has only ONE instance and provides a global point of access to it. Implementation: private constructor, private static instance, public static getInstance() method. ```cpp
class Singleton {
private:
    static Singleton* instance;
    Singleton() {}
public:
    static Singleton* getInstance() {
        if (!instance) instance = new Singleton();
        return instance;
    }
};
```
Use cases: Database connection pool, logger, configuration manager — resources that should exist once. Drawbacks: 1) Hard to unit test (global state). 2) Violates Single Responsibility. 3) Thread-safety issues with lazy initialization. 4) Hidden dependencies. Often considered an anti-pattern.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Vehicle {
public:
    virtual void start() = 0;  // pure virtual
    virtual void stop() = 0;   // pure virtual
    virtual ~Vehicle() {}      // virtual destructor

    void fuel() {  // concrete method
        cout << "Refueling..." << endl;
    }
};

class Car : public Vehicle {
public:
    void start() override {
        cout << "Car engine starting..." << endl;
    }
    void stop() override {
        cout << "Car engine stopping..." << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Vehicle* v = new Car();
    v->start();
    v->fuel();
    v->stop();
    delete v;
    return 0;
}
```
Pure virtual functions (= 0) make Vehicle abstract — cannot instantiate directly. Car must implement all pure virtual functions.

Templates allow writing generic code that works with any data type. The compiler generates specific versions for each type used. Function template:
```cpp
template <typename T>
T maximum(T a, T b) {
    return (a > b) ? a : b;
}
// Usage: maximum(5, 10); maximum(3.14, 2.71);
```
Class template: template<typename T> class Stack { T data[100]; ... };
Benefits: Code reuse, type-safe, no runtime overhead (resolved at compile time). The STL (Standard Template Library) is built on templates — vector<T>, map<K,V>, etc. Templates are a compile-time mechanism, unlike Java generics which use type erasure at runtime.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Complex {
private:
    double real, imag;
public:
    Complex(double r = 0, double i = 0) : real(r), imag(i) {}

    Complex operator+(const Complex& other) const {
        return Complex(real + other.real, imag + other.imag);
    }

    void display() const {
        cout << real << " + " << imag << "i" << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Complex c1(3, 4), c2(1, 2);
    Complex c3 = c1 + c2;
    c3.display(); // Output: 4 + 6i
    return 0;
}
```
Operator overloading gives custom meaning to operators for user-defined types. The + operator returns a new Complex object. Use const reference parameter and const method.
